    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Collectively, the class of sculptures, containers, and other objects and artifacts carved in jade, which is any of several varieties of fine-grained rock composed of jadeite, nephrite, serpentine, or other mineralogically related materials. Prominent examples of jades include carved jade objects produced in China from the Neolithic Period (ca. 3000–2000 BCE) onward. The Chinese have historically regarded carved-jade objects as intrinsically valuable, and they metaphorically equated jade with purity and indestructibility. In local the material term "jade (rock)" plus a more specific object name may be used, such as "jade (rock)" + "figurines."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079228/Grove Art Online (2008-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Úsese colectivamente para la clase de objetos tallados en jade. Cuando sea posible, use el término del material más un nombre más espcífico para el objeto, tal como "jade" + "estatuilla".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Het Nederlands kent het zelfstandig naamwoord 'jade' om een object van jade aan te duiden niet. Gebruik daarom liever de materiaalbenaming in combinatie met de objectbenaming: 'jade' + 'beeldhouwwerken'.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>以玉為材料雕刻而成的雕塑、容器、其他物件或人造品之總稱。在適當的情況下，可在材質名稱後加上特定的物件名稱，例如「玉」加「小雕像」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Zusammengefasst die Gruppe von Skulpturen, Behältnissen und anderen Objekten und Artfakten, die aus Jade geschnitzt sind. Berühmte Beispiele sind die geschnitzten Jade-Objekte aus China aus dem Neolithikum (ca. 3000-2000 v. Chr.) und später. Die Chinesen haben in der Geschichte aus Jade geschnitzte Objekte als Wertgegenstände angesehen und sie setzten Jade mit Reinheit und Unzerstörbarkeit gleich. Wenn möglich wird der Materialbegriff zusammen mit dem speziellen Namen des Objekts verwendet, wie “Jade” + “Figurine”.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Coletivamente, a classe de esculturas, recipientes e outros objetos e artefatos esculpidos em jade, que é qualquer uma das muitas variedades de rocha em grãos finos composta de jadeita, nefrita, serpentina ou outros materiais minerais relacionados. Exemplos proeminentes de jades incluem objetos de jade esculpidos produzidos na China do Período Neolitico (ca. 3000-2000 a.C.) em diante. Historicamente, os chineses consideram objetos de jade esculpidos como intrinsecamente valiosos e eles, metaforicamente, equiparam jade com pureza e indestrutibilidade. O termo material "jade (rocha)" junto com o nome de objeto mais específico pode ser usado, por exemplo, "jade (rocha)" + "estátuas".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
